import requests

def get_total_count(url):
    try:
        response = requests.get(url)
        response.raise_for_status()  # Check if the request was successful
        if response.text:  # Check if the response is not empty
            return response.json()
        else:
            print("The response is empty.")
            return None
    except requests.exceptions.HTTPError as http_err:
        print(f"HTTP error occurred: {http_err}")
    except requests.exceptions.RequestException as req_err:
        print(f"Request error occurred: {req_err}")
    except requests.exceptions.JSONDecodeError as json_err:
        print(f"JSON decode error occurred: {json_err}")
    return None

# Example usage
url = 'https://data.cityofchicago.org/resource/cwig-ma7x.json'
total_count = get_total_count(url)
print(total_count)

%%time

# Define the API endpoint and parameters
url = "https://data.cityofchicago.org/resource/cwig-ma7x.json"

# Fetch the total count of records
def get_total_count(url):
    params = {
        "$select": "count(*)"
    }
    response = requests.get(url, params=params)
    data = response.json()
    return int(data[0]['count'])

total_count = get_total_count(url)
print(f"Total number of records available: {total_count:,.0f}")

Total number of records available: 273,851
CPU times: user 17.5 ms, sys: 2.91 ms, total: 20.4 ms
Wall time: 398 ms
In [4]:
%%time

# Fetch data and load it into a pandas DataFrame
def fetch_data(url, params):
    response = requests.get(url, params=params)
    data = response.json()
    return pd.DataFrame(data)

# Set the limit parameter equal to the number of available records
params = {
    "$limit": total_count
}

# Fetch the data and load it into a DataFrame
df = fetch_data(url, params)

print(f'Number of records retrieved: {df.shape[0]:,.0f}')

Number of records retrieved: 273,851
CPU times: user 8.95 s, sys: 1.4 s, total: 10.3 s
Wall time: 45.8 s

4. Using regular expression, parse "violations" column to select only regulation descriptions, no code or comments¶

In [11]:
# Let's define a function that select only description and no code / comment
def extract_descriptions(text):
    matches = re.findall(r'\d+\.\s*([^|-]+)', text)
    # Saw that we were getting MUST PROVIDE incorrectly. Modified below to remove those.
    cleaned_matches = [re.split(r'\s-\sComments:|MUST PROVIDE', match)[0].strip() for match in matches]
    # Remove any blanks / empty values
    cleaned_matches = list(filter(None, cleaned_matches))
    return cleaned_matches

failed_inspections_cleaned['violation_descriptions'] = failed_inspections_cleaned['violations'].apply(extract_descriptions)
failed_inspections_cleaned['violation_descriptions'].apply(tuple).unique()[2]

In [18]:
repeat_offenders_merged = failed_inspections_cleaned.merge(repeat_offenders, on=['license_', 'dba_name', 'address'], how='inner')
repeat_offenders_merged

# Let's see what violations are repeated by these restaurants
flattened_data = []
for index, row in repeat_offenders_merged.iterrows():
    license_ = row['license_']
    dba_name = row['dba_name']
    address = row['address']
    for violation in row['violation_descriptions']:
        flattened_data.append({
            'license_': license_,
            'dba_name': dba_name,
            'address': address,
            'violation_description': violation
        })

# Create a DataFrame from the flattened data
flattened_df = pd.DataFrame(flattened_data)

# Count the occurrences of each violation description
violation_counts = flattened_df.groupby(['license_', 'dba_name', 'address', 'violation_description']).size().reset_index(name='offense_count')
violation_counts.sort_values(by= ['address', 'dba_name', 'offense_count'], ascending=[True, True, False])

# We can see there are some violations that are same for these repeat offenses and some are different

# Let's take failed inspection data that we have already cleaned and use inspection_date for looking at
# trend history in 5 most common violations

failed_inspections_cleaned

# Flatten the list of violation descriptions and display the top 5 most frequent regulation descriptions

In [29]:
violation_trends = pd.DataFrame({'inspection_year': sorted(failed_inspections_top_5_violations['inspection_year'].unique())})

# Count occurrences of each top 5 violation per year
for violation in top_5_violations:
    violation_rows = failed_inspections_top_5_violations[failed_inspections_top_5_violations['violation_descriptions'].apply(lambda x: violation in x)]
    yearly_counts = violation_rows.groupby('inspection_year').size().reset_index(name=violation)
    violation_trends = pd.merge(violation_trends, yearly_counts, on='inspection_year', how='left')

violation_trends.fillna(0, inplace=True)

# Plot the trends for the top 5 most frequent violations over time
plt.figure(figsize=(14, 8))
for violation in top_5_violations:
    plt.plot(violation_trends['inspection_year'], violation_trends[violation], label=violation[:33])
plt.xlabel('Year')
plt.ylabel('# Violations')
plt.title('Trends in Top 5 Most Frequent Food Inspection Violations Over Time')
plt.legend(title='Violation Description', bbox_to_anchor=(1.05, 1), loc='upper left')
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

# We see that among the top 5 common violations, 4 violations completely dropped over time 
# and other violation types picked up showing that the data capturing had some change in 2018
# Physical facilities installed picked up in 2018 and then dropped in 2020 (possibly COVID related?) but continued
# over time 2024 data is not full so I expected a drop there in trend
# Top 10 most frequent food inspection violations shows a better trend story

In [30]:
violation_trends = pd.DataFrame({'inspection_year': sorted(failed_inspections_top_10_violations['inspection_year'].unique())})

# Count occurrences of each top 10 violation per year
for violation in top_10_violations:
    violation_rows = failed_inspections_top_10_violations[failed_inspections_top_10_violations['violation_descriptions'].apply(lambda x: violation in x)]
    yearly_counts = violation_rows.groupby('inspection_year').size().reset_index(name=violation)
    violation_trends = pd.merge(violation_trends, yearly_counts, on='inspection_year', how='left')

violation_trends.fillna(0, inplace=True)

# Plot the trends for the top 10 most frequent violations over time
plt.figure(figsize=(14, 8))
for violation in top_10_violations:
    plt.plot(violation_trends['inspection_year'], violation_trends[violation], label=violation[:33])
plt.xlabel('Year')
plt.ylabel('# Violations')
plt.title('Trends in Top 10 Most Frequent Food Inspection Violations Over Time')
plt.legend(title='Violation Description', bbox_to_anchor=(1.05, 1), loc='upper left')
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

# As you see the data has some switch change in 2018 causing the trend plot to not show a continous story
# Mentioned in the dataset site too: https://data.cityofchicago.org/Health-Human-Services/Food-Inspections/4ijn-s7e5/about_data
# "Note about 7/1/2018 change to food inspection procedures that affects the data in this dataset: http://bit.ly/2yWd2JB"

# Separate interesting note: During COVID violations were down but ramped up post that
